{'project_name': 'Jinjia Jiayi CMM Power Generation Project', 'project_summary': 'Jinjia Jiayi CMM Power Generation Project (hereafter referred to as “the Project”) is located in Xiaochong Village, Pan County, Liupanshui City, Guizhou Province, People’s Republic of China.The purpose of the Project is to utilize the extracted coal mine methane (CMM) with a low concentration of methane to produce electricity. No coal bed methane (CBM) or ventilation air methane (VAM) utilization is involved. 

Six sets of CMM power generators are installed with a total installed capacity of 3.6 MW (6×0.6 MW). When all six power generators are in full operation, the Project is expected to export 17,280 MWh of electricity and destroy 7.2 million m3 (under normal conditions ) of methane every year. The generated electricity is supplied to the coal mines through the electricity distribution network in the Jinjia coal mine area; part of the electricity produced by the Project may also be exported to CSPG if there is any electricity surplus after the coal mine demand is fully met, thus displacing part of the electricity generated by CSPG dominated by fossil fuel-fired power plants.

The Project achieves emission reductions in two aspects: 1) it reduces methane emissions by capturing and destroying methane which would have been directly vented into the air in the baseline scenario; 2) it reduces CO2 emissions by displacing part of the electricity that would otherwise have been supplied by CSPG.', 'project_state_province': 'Guizhou', 'project_country': 'China', 'project_latitude': 25.65, 'project_longitude': 104.5}
